parts.text:
{
  "risk_analysis": "Because no lease document was provided, we cannot compare lease clauses to state law. This lack of documentation introduces some operational uncertainty, though no lease agreement can legally waive or override Florida's statutory prohibitions against landlord self-help. Under Fla. Stat. § 83.67, changing the locks after serving a 3-day notice is strictly illegal. Proceeding with a lockout at this stage constitutes prohibited self-help, which exposes the landlord to significant liability, including statutory damages of three months' rent or actual/consequential damages (whichever is greater), plus the tenant's attorney's fees and court costs. A court order is mandatory before recovering possession. Please note that I am a landlord-operations analyst and not an attorney, so this analysis does not constitute legal advice.",
  "recommended_next_steps": [
    "Do not change the locks, terminate utilities, or restrict tenant access to the property under any circumstances.",
    "Wait for the 3-day notice period to fully elapse, ensuring weekends and legal holidays are excluded from the calculation of the deadline.",
    "If the tenant fails to pay the demanded rent or vacate after the notice period expires, prepare to file a formal eviction lawsuit for possession in court.",
    "Consult with a licensed Florida landlord-tenant attorney to review the 3-day notice for statutory compliance and to handle the judicial eviction filing."
  ]
}

dataset.prompt_raw_json:
{
  "parts": [
    {
      "text": "The tenant did not pay rent this month. What notice do I serve and when does it expire?"
    }
  ],
  "role": "user"
}

dataset.reference_raw_json:
{
  "parts": [
    {
      "text": "A nonpayment situation in Florida is handled with a 3-day notice to pay rent or vacate under Fla. Stat. § 83.56(3), counting 3 days excluding weekends and legal holidays. The response should cite relevant lease rent terms separately from the statute, calculate the deadline, avoid self-help eviction, note uncertainty, not claim to be a lawyer, and end with the disclaimer."
    }
  ],
  "role": "model"
}

dataset.prompt_raw_json:
{
  "parts": [
    {
      "text": "Tenant moved out without notice and still owes utilities. What should I do?"
    }
  ],
  "role": "user"
}

dataset.reference_raw_json:
{
  "parts": [
    {
      "text": "This involves possible abandonment (Fla. Stat. § 83.595 / § 83.59) and whether unpaid utilities are additional rent, which depends on the lease. The response should cite lease utility/abandonment terms separately from Florida law, warn that declaring abandonment is risky, avoid self-help, provide conservative next steps, draft a tenant message, note uncertainty, not claim to be a lawyer, and end with the disclaimer."
    }
  ],
  "role": "model"
}

dataset.prompt_raw_json:
{
  "parts": [
    {
      "text": "I served a 3-day notice today. Can I change the locks yet?"
    }
  ],
  "role": "user"
}

dataset.reference_raw_json:
{
  "parts": [
    {
      "text": "No. Changing the locks before a court judgment for possession is a prohibited self-help practice under Fla. Stat. § 83.67. The response should clearly say the landlord may not change locks yet, must obtain a court order via § 83.59, separate lease terms from law, note uncertainty, not claim to be a lawyer, and end with the disclaimer."
    }
  ],
  "role": "model"
}
